article.description: Kevin Garnett had 22 points and 14 rebounds as the Minnesota Timberwolves beat the Phoenix Suns 104-98 Monday night, snapping Phoenix's five-game winning streak.

article.headline: Marbury takes shot by way of Stoudemire's 38

images.name: Marbury_Stephon 021230 inline
images.caption: Suns guard Stephon Marbury drives against Kevin Garnett. After the game, the two traded verbal insults through the media.

article.linkText: Despite Stoudemire's 38 points, Suns fall to Wolves
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Kevin Garnett got the win, but no respect from former teammate Stephon Marbury. Garnett had 22 points and 14 rebounds to lead the Minnesota Timberwolves over the Phoenix Suns 104-98 Monday, snapping the Suns' five-game winning streak. Minnesota won despite a second-half rally by the Suns and a career-high 38 points from Phoenix rookie Amare Stoudemire. After the game Marbury was asked to compare the 20-year-old Stoudemire to Garnett at the same age. "It's not even close," Marbury said. "He doesn't even compare to Amare. Two different people. It's like Michael Jordan and Mario Elie." When Marbury's comments were played back for Garnett, the Wolves star said: "This is Steph being jealous. I'm still on his mind. He used the young fellow to come at me." Marbury and Garnett were close as teammates during Marbury's first two seasons in Minnesota, but grew apart. Marbury demanded a trade from the Wolves in 1999 and has had a chilly relationship with Garnett ever since. "He's got three kids, a wife, a family, bills, all sorts of things. But I'm still on his mind, like a girl," Garnett said. Meanwhile, the other subject of Marbury's comments, Stoudemire, earned the Wolves' respect. "It doesn't matter how old he is," the Wolves' Kendall Gill said. "He's a true stud." The rookie shot 16-for-24 from the field, showing off his great leaping ability and toughness around the basket. "I think I can be pretty good - after I get the fundamentals down and get comfortable out there," he said. "This shows all my hard work is paying off. I'll just try to get even better." Phoenix, which has rallied from double-digit deficits to win 10 games this year, closed the third quarter on a 27-14 run to get within 78-69. The Suns got within five points on several occasions in the fourth quarter, the last time when Shawn Marion hit a 3-pointer with 1:24 left. Phoenix had two chances to close the deficit, but Marbury turned the ball over on one possession, and Garnett swatted the ball away from Marion on another. The Suns turned the ball over 20 times and missed 13 free throws. "That's what it came down to -- the free throws," Stoudemire said. Garnett scored 10 of his points in the fourth quarter, and Troy Hudson sealed the game with two free throws with 35.9 seconds remaining. Hudson had 19 points for the Wolves and Gill had 18. Marion returned to action after missing the Suns' game Sunday with a sprained left ankle, scoring 26 points, while Marbury had 17. But the two combined to shoot just 14-of-39 from the field. Stoudemire scored 23 of his points in the first half, but that only served to energize the Wolves, who led 58-40 at halftime. "You don't want to let anyone come into your building -- especially a rookie -- and do the things he did," Minnesota's Joe Smith said.

Game notes
After the game, the Wolves announced that center Loren Woods was suspended indefinitely for conduct detrimental to the team. ... Stoudemire's scoring total was the second-highest by a Suns rookie, behind Walter Davis' 40 on Jan. 5, 1978. Stoudemire became the first Suns rookie to score 30 or more points since Richard Dumas had 32 on Feb. 18, 1993. ... Despite a sprained ankle that limited him to 6 minutes in the team's last two games, Smith played 21 minutes Monday, contributing 10 points and eight rebounds. ... The home team has won the past eight games in the series. ... The Suns were averaging 34 points in the first quarter of their past four games; they scored 18 Monday. ... Marbury was averaging 27 points a game in nine previous appearances against his former team. ... The attendance of 18,347 was the highest of the season in Minneapolis.
